🚀 1. FULL OLYMPIC CHARTER DRAFT — SPACE RACE OLYMPICS

PREAMBLE

The Space Race Olympics (SRO) exists to advance human exploration, scientific literacy, peaceful cooperation, and athletic excellence beyond Earth.
This Charter establishes the mission, ethics, safety standards, eligibility, governance, and operational structure for all SRO events, simulations, and training programs.

---

ARTICLE I — MISSION

1. To create the first interplanetary athletic competition grounded in safety, science, and stewardship.
2. To inspire children and adults to pursue aerospace, engineering, teamwork, and peaceful exploration.
3. To ensure all competitions reflect fairness, transparency, and respect for human dignity.
4. To maintain strict separation between live competitions and public simulation modes, ensuring safety and integrity.


---

ARTICLE II — CORE VALUES

• Safety First — No competition or training supersedes human life or environmental protection.
• Stewardship — All actions must honor Earth, space environments, and future generations.
• Fair Play — Equal access, no cheating, no interference, no unauthorized modifications.
• Education — Every event must teach physics, navigation, teamwork, and emotional regulation.
• Peaceful Intent — No militarization, no weapons, no hostile maneuvers.
• Transparency — Rules, scoring, and safety protocols must be publicly documented.


---

ARTICLE III — GOVERNANCE

1. The SRO is overseen by the Interplanetary Athletics Council (IAC).
2. The IAC includes:• Aerospace engineers
• Safety officers
• Educators
• Medical experts
• Athlete representatives
• Youth advisors

3. All rule changes require a ⅔ majority vote.
4. Emergency safety overrides may be enacted by the Chief Safety Officer.


---

ARTICLE IV — EVENT CATEGORIES

1. Orbital Racing

• Piloting precision
• Thruster control
• Zero‑G maneuvering
• Heat‑management challenges


2. Docking Trials

• Accuracy
• Timing
• Stability under rotation


3. Terrain Navigation

• Lunar, Martian, or simulated asteroid surfaces
• Traction management
• Hazard avoidance


4. Endurance & Systems Management

• Thermal regulation
• Energy conservation
• Multi‑phase mission planning


5. Youth Simulation League (YSL)

• Non‑competitive
• No live‑race interaction
• Educational and safe


---

ARTICLE V — ELIGIBILITY

Professional Division

• Age 18+
• Certified medical clearance
• Completion of SRO Advanced Training
• Zero disciplinary violations


Youth Division (Simulation Only)

• Ages 6–17
• Strictly digital or controlled‑arena participation
• No physical spaceflight
• Parent/guardian consent


---

ARTICLE VI — SAFETY PROTOCOLS

1. All vehicles must pass pre‑flight inspection.
2. No exposed spikes, claws, or traction devices during launch, reentry, or docking.
3. Emergency override systems must be accessible to pilots and safety officers.
4. All live events must include:• Redundant life‑support
• Collision‑avoidance AI
• Thermal shielding
• Remote abort capability

5. Youth simulations must:• Cap speed
• Use padded arenas
• Include emotional cooldown breaks
• Provide AI-assisted driving correction



---

ARTICLE VII — ETHICS

1. No sabotage, interference, or unauthorized modifications.
2. No exploitation of children or minors.
3. No environmental contamination of celestial bodies.
4. No political or military use of SRO platforms.
5. All participants must uphold the Steward’s Oath: “I race not for dominance, but for discovery.
I compete not to conquer, but to learn.
I honor the stars, the Earth, and all who follow.”


---

ARTICLE VIII — TECHNOLOGY & EQUIPMENT

1. All propulsion systems must meet safety certification.
2. No classified or military hardware allowed.
3. All youth vehicles must be:• Low‑speed
• Padded
• Geo‑locked
• Non‑weaponized

4. All simulation software must be open to audit.


---

ARTICLE IX — SCORING & JUDGING

• Transparent scoring
• Automated telemetry logs
• Human judges + AI verification
• Appeals allowed within 24 hours


---

ARTICLE X — AMENDMENTS

This Charter may be amended as technology evolves, but the core values of safety, stewardship, and education may never be removed.

